Thanks guys. I agree we need to avoid retrying.

In the new push, I added a mechanism to limit sending such a request to once while local network data remains unchanged. This way if leader does not response we won't keep trying. Here is the comment about this:

```c++
    // We allow device to request router role upgrade using status
    // reason `kBorderRouterRequst` once while its local network data
    // remains unchanged. This ensures if the leader is running an
    // older version of Thread stack which does not support
    // `kBorderRouterRequst` reason, we do not keep trying (on no
    // response). The boolean `mDidRequestRouterRoleUpgrade` tracks
    // this. It is set to `false` when local network data get changed
    // or when partition ID gets changed (indicating a potential
    // leader change).
```

I think @EskoDijk described leader behavior nicely. 😃 
The OT code before https://github.com/openthread/openthread/pull/7578 would simply ignore the request (no response would be sent and reading the `Coap` code, I think no CoAP ack either).  But from sender side, the request will be timed out after some number of attempts (by `Coap` layer). Since we now limit this to one request, it should be ok to try once and time out.

The error isn't because they aren't assignable. The panic is due to `resolved.Type().Elem()` which panics if the kind is not one of a specified list:

from libexec/src/reflect/type.go
```go
func (t *rtype) Elem() Type {
	switch t.Kind() {
	case Array:
		tt := (*arrayType)(unsafe.Pointer(t))
		return toType(tt.elem)
	case Chan:
		tt := (*chanType)(unsafe.Pointer(t))
		return toType(tt.elem)
	case Map:
		tt := (*mapType)(unsafe.Pointer(t))
		return toType(tt.elem)
	case Ptr:
		tt := (*ptrType)(unsafe.Pointer(t))
		return toType(tt.elem)
	case Slice:
		tt := (*sliceType)(unsafe.Pointer(t))
		return toType(tt.elem)
	}
	panic("reflect: Elem of invalid type")
}
```

I checked and this is indeed a bit more complicated than how it's currently handled by this PR. The way I see it, we have two options: require that every stream using the Scorer has finished before allowing one to disable it, or making it so that the actual scorer instance is only destroyed when the last stream using it is finished.

The former is an awkward API, as it's pretty much a non-recoverable failure. The latter can lead to memory leaks if an application doesn't close its streams. I think an application not closing its streams is not a common scenario, as all of the "Finish" functions take care of that. So I'm partial to just deferring scorer destruction until the last stream is finished. 

